{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:58:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:58:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16758"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.6,0.23,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2681"},{"type":"tags","id":"3843"},{"type":"tags","id":"3879"},{"type":"tags","id":"4219"},{"type":"tags","id":"4769"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22332"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a six-month history of vulval itch and discomfort. She has tried over-the-counter antifungal creams without improvement. She experienced menopause at age 51 and has never used hormone replacement therapy. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. She has never smoked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Vulval examination reveals a 2 cm raised, white plaque on the right labium majus with surrounding erythema. There is no lymphadenopathy in the inguinal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral for colposcopy","Topical clotrimazole for two weeks","Vulval biopsy in outpatient clinic","Topical hydrocortisone for one week","Oral fluconazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic vulval symptoms and an abnormal vulval lesion that has not responded to empiric antifungal treatment. The presence of a raised white plaque in a postmenopausal woman raises concern for vulval intraepithelial neoplasia or invasive vulval cancer. Given these findings and the duration of symptoms, tissue diagnosis is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVulval biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step to establish a definitive diagnosis. This is typically performed as a punch biopsy under local anaesthetic in the outpatient setting. The biopsy should include the edge of any lesion and adjacent normal tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clotrimazole\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the patient has already failed empiric antifungal treatment. Additionally, the clinical appearance is not typical for vulvovaginal candidiasis, which usually presents with erythema and white discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate without first establishing a diagnosis, as corticosteroids could mask or exacerbate an underlying condition such as infection or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not the appropriate first step as colposcopy is primarily used for cervical examination. While a vulvoscopy would be appropriate to look at the vulva the concern here is the vulva not the cervix. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given the failure of topical antifungal therapy and the suspicious appearance of the lesion. Systemic antifungal therapy without a definitive diagnosis could delay the identification of a more serious condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vulval biopsy is indicated for persistent vulval symptoms or lesions that do not respond to initial therapy.","Vulval intraepithelial neoplasia and vulval cancer are important differential diagnoses in postmenopausal women with persistent vulval symptoms.","Punch biopsy under local anaesthetic is the preferred method for tissue diagnosis of vulval lesions."],"references":["Vieira-Baptista P, P\u00e9rez-L\u00f3pez FR, L\u00f3pez-Baena MT, Stockdale CK, Preti M, Bornstein J. Risk of Development of Vulvar Cancer in Women With Lichen Sclerosus or Lichen Planus: A Systematic Review. J Low Genit Tract Dis. 2022 Jul 1;26(3):250-257. doi: 10.1097/LGT.0000000000000673. Epub 2022 Mar 11. PMID: 35285455."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T15:26:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T15:27:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66817"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,